   *Offer expires 2/20/13, 9 a.m. E.S.T. Mobile apps are not supported on all devices. Does not include e-reader editions, Premium Crosswords or The New York Times' Crosswords apps. Home delivery
   offer available for readers who have not had home delivery within the past 90 days. Other restrictions apply.

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

     * Privacy Policy
     * Contact Us
     * Help

The Oldest No. 1, and the Newest Rivalry

By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY

   Serena Williams, 31, lost to Victoria Azarenka on Sunday, but passed her atop the WTA rankings.

Mohammed Dabbous/Reuters

   Serena Williams, 31, lost to Victoria Azarenka on Sunday, but passed her atop the WTA rankings.

   However you analyze it, Serena Williams’s return to No. 1 should rank high on a list of career achievements that already includes 15 Grand Slam singles titles.
   Of the harsh criticism about her, Rebecca Marino said, “With professional athletes, people put them on a pedestal sometimes, and they forget that they’re actually a person still.”

Player Overcomes Bullying and a Hiatus

By BEN ROTHENBERG

   Rebecca Marino has a fresh mind-set after taking a break from the WTA Tour because of threats and harsh criticism on the Internet.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

See the world differently with the International Herald Tribune

   The IHT combines the extensive international reporting of The Times with the IHT’s distinctive, sophisticated perspective on what’s happening around the world and what it means. Subscribe today
   to the IHT Smartphone or All Digital Access packages for full access to IHT apps and NYTimes.com. IHT All Digital Access also includes the IHT app for iPad with more than 18 international
   sections fully refreshed for Europe and Asia mornings, plus the latest news from global.nytimes.com, videos, Day in Pictures, and extras like cartoons and business travel guides.
   International Herald Tribune
   International Herald Tribune

Frequently Asked Questions

   Back to Top

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?To get unlimited access to IHT apps, you’ll now need a subscription. When you subscribe to the IHT Smartphone or All Digital Access
   packages you’ll also get unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site and mobile site including 100 Archive articles every four weeks. IHT digital subscriptions do not include e-reader editions
   or any New York Times-branded smartphone or tablet apps.

   What is the difference between International Herald Tribune and New York Times apps?The International Herald Tribune is the global edition of The New York Times and combines the extensive
   resources of its own correspondents with those of The Times to give its internationally engaged readers a distinctive global perspective on geopolitics, business, sports, culture and more. The
   IHT apps for smartphones and the iPad are refreshed for Europe and Asia mornings from the IHT news hubs in Hong Kong, Paris and New York and include the latest news from global.nytimes.com.
   International Herald Tribune Users

   Can I get apps from both the IHT and NYT in one package?At this time, it is not possible to purchase one single digital subscription that includes access to both IHT and NYT apps. If you wish,
   for example, to buy both the IHT app for iPad and the NYTimes app for iPad, you would need to buy two separate subscriptions. However, IHT Smartphone and All Digital Access packages do include
   full access to NYTimes.com, as does the IHT home delivery subscription.
   International Herald Tribune Users

   I get home delivery of the IHT newspaper. Do I get free access?Yes. Paid home delivery subscribers to the International Herald Tribune who purchase at least five days per week get a free IHT All
   Digital Access subscription, which includes full access to the IHT apps for iPhone, Android and iPad, plus full access to NYTimes.com on any device.

   In some countries, home delivery of the newspaper is provided by a local partner or franchise, rather than by the International Herald Tribune directly. In most cases, customers in these
   countries will also be able to obtain free access to the IHT All Digital Access package. Please check with your local customer service office for more information.

   To activate your digital subscription to the International Herald Tribune, click here.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?You can cancel your IHT digital subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing
   cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterwards, you will still be able to view 10 articles per month on NYTimes.com and
   read unlocked articles on our apps at no charge, just like any other visitor.

   View the full cancellation and refund policy »

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?All visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar
   month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100
   Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that both NYTimes and IHT apps are free to download and install, and offer a limited number of articles for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to
   all articles, multimedia and tools within the apps.

   View our complete FAQ »

   sections fully refreshed for the Europe and Asia mornings and the latest news feed from global.nytimes.com, the IHT’s app for iPad keeps you abreast of what’s happening in the world and what it
   means, wherever you are.

   Additional features include: videos, Day in Pictures, world weather tool, article sharing, daily cartoons and business travel guides for India, China and the Middle East.

Help

   Help > Managing My Account > Digital Subscriptions and Premium Products > IHT Digital Subscriptions

IHT Digital Subscriptions

     * 1. What is an IHT digital subscription? How much does it cost?
     * 2. I get home delivery of The International Herald Tribune newspaper. Do I get free access?
     * 3. What if I don’t want to subscribe – can I still read NYTimes.com for free?
     * 4. Why do I get only 10 articles free on NYTimes.com each month?
     * 5. How are digital subscriptions billed?
     * 6. I’m outside the United States. How will my subscription price be calculated?
     * 7. Can I get access on my smartphone or tablet? What devices are supported?
     * 8. What is the cancellation and refund policy?
     * 9. Can I get a digital subscription to the NYTimes.com Web site only?
     * 10. I have an existing IHT digital subscription. Can I also access apps and other products from The New York Times?
     * 11. What is the difference between International Herald Tribune and New York Times apps?
     * 12. Can I get both NYTimes and IHT apps in one package?
     * 13. Are there any subscription discounts?
     * 14. Can I still access NYTimes.com articles through Facebook, Twitter, search engines or my blog?
     * 15. I am a home delivery customer. How do I activate my free, unlimited digital access?
     * 16. I am currently an International Herald Tribune home delivery subscriber and have already linked my accounts for my IHT All Digital Access. Do I still have access to the NYTimes apps?
     * 17. Are eReader apps (e.g. IHT for Kindle, IHT for Nook) included in IHT All Digital Access?
     * 18. I’m not currently a digital subscriber. What kind of content counts toward my monthly limit on NYTimes.com? Do I get access to anything?
     * 19. How do I download the apps that are included with my digital subscription?
     * 20. How do I log in to the IHT apps?
     * 21. Is there any free content within the IHT apps?
     * 22. What is a "section front" or "blog front"?
     * 23. How can I keep track of how many articles I have read on NYTimes.com each month?
     * 24. If I go back and read an article I’ve already read, will that count toward my monthly limit on NYTimes.com?
     * 25. Do comments count toward my monthly limit?
     * 26. Can I access my digital subscription on more than one computer, smartphone or tablet?
     * 27. How do I change the e-mail address that’s associated with my digital subscription?
     * 28. Can I give someone a digital subscription as a gift?
     * 29. Do you offer free trial subscriptions?
     * 30. I am affiliated with a college or university. Can I get a digital subscription discount?
     * 31. I have a subscription to the IHT on my Kindle, or other e-reader. Does this give me access to NYTimes.com?
     * 32. Can I create more than one NYTimes.com account that corresponds to my subscription? Do you offer a “family plan”?
     * 33. I’ve signed up for NYTimes.com e-mail newsletters. Will e-mail newsletters be affected by digital subscriptions?
     * 34. Will you offer subscription apps on tablets other than the iPad?
     * 35. My question was not answered here. How can I get more information?
     * 36. How do I send you my feedback on digital subscriptions and products?

     * 1. What is an IHT digital subscription? How much does it cost?
       Back to top
       There are currently three IHT digital subscriptions options:
       IHT Smartphone app + NYTimes.com:* $3.75 per week (billed every 4 weeks at $15.00)
          + IHT app for iPhone and Android-powered phones
          + NYTimes.com from any computer or device
       IHT Tablet App:* $3.75 per week (billed every 4 weeks at $15.00)
          + IHT app for iPad
       IHT All Digital Access:* $6.25 per week (billed every 4 weeks at $25.00)
          + IHT app for iPhone and Android-powered phones
          + IHT app for iPad
          + NYTimes.com from any computer or device
       *Note: IHT apps are not supported on all devices. IHT digital subscriptions do not include e-reader editions (e.g., Kindle, Nook, Sony Reader, Kobo Reader), or any NYTimes apps for any
       device. Additional restrictions apply.
       Home Delivery:
       All paid IHT home delivery subscribers who subscribe for a minimum of five days per week get the IHT All Digital Access package for free. To activate your digital subscription, you'll need to
       connect your home delivery subscription to your NYTimes.com account. If you haven't already done so, visit this page to connect your accounts.
       Additional Benefits:
       Digital subscribers receive access to the New York Times archives, including 100 free articles from 1923 through 1986 every four weeks. Archived articles outside the 1923–1986 date range are
       free to subscribers at all times and do not have the 100-article limit.
     * 2. I get home delivery of The International Herald Tribune newspaper. Do I get free access?
       Back to top
       Yes. Paid home delivery subscribers to The International Herald Tribune who purchase at least five days per week get a free IHT All Digital Access subscription, which includes full access to
       the IHT apps for iPhone and iPad, plus full access to NYTimes.com on any device.
       In some countries, home delivery of the newspaper is provided by a local partner or franchise, rather than by the International Herald Tribune directly. In most cases, customers in these
       countries will also be able to obtain free access to the IHT All Digital Access package. Please check with your local customer service office for more information.
       Activate your digital subscription to the International Herald Tribune »
     * 3. What if I don’t want to subscribe – can I still read NYTimes.com for free?
       Back to top
       Visitors can enjoy 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as unrestricted access to browse the
       home page, section fronts, blog fronts and classifieds.
       Your free, limited access resets every month: at the beginning of each calendar month, you'll once again be able to view 10 free articles for that month.
       Here are a few examples of "section fronts":
       Politics | Arts | Opinion
       And here are some examples of "blog fronts":
       Well | Bits | City Room
       For nonsubscribers, articles from the New York Times archives from 1923 through 1986 are $3.95 each. Views of archived articles outside that date range are free but still count toward the
       10-article monthly limit.
     * 4. Why do I get only 10 articles free on NYTimes.com each month?
       Back to top
       The New York Times and the International Herald Tribune have begun charging for unlimited access to their digital content. We're doing this so we can continue to invest in the quality
       journalism you know and love. We've set the limit high enough that many readers won't encounter it. But if you're a regular reader, we hope you'll consider subscribing. You'll get unlimited
       access to all of our content, including articles, blog posts, video, slide shows and other multimedia features — on the Web site, on the mobile site and on our smartphone and tablet apps.
       Read the letter from our publisher »
     * 5. How are digital subscriptions billed?
       Back to top
       We accept major credit cards and PayPal. Subscriptions are billed every four weeks. Your subscription will be renewed automatically, and you will be charged in advance of each billing cycle
       unless you cancel.
     * 6. I’m outside the United States. How will my subscription price be calculated?
       Back to top
       All NYTimes and IHT subscription prices are in United States dollars. If you're outside the United States, we'll calculate your subscription price each billing cycle (every 4 weeks), based on
       the exchange rate at the time of the calculation.
     * 7. Can I get access on my smartphone or tablet? What devices are supported?
       Back to top
       The IHT Smartphone app + NYTimes.com package and the IHT All Digital Access package both include unlimited access to NYTimes.com on any computer or device. The IHT Tablet app subscription
       does not include NYTimes.com access.
       View the available IHT apps for smartphones and tablets »
     * 8. What is the cancellation and refund policy?
       Back to top
       You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
       continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read the Front Page section on our apps at no
       charge, just like any other visitor.
     * 9. Can I get a digital subscription to the NYTimes.com Web site only?
       Back to top
       No. To receive access to NYTimes.com you must subscribe to the IHT Smartphone app + NYTimes.com package or the IHT All Digital Access package, which both give you ongoing access to
       NYTimes.com on any computer or device. Please note, International Herald Tribune home delivery subscribers receive a complimentary IHT All Digital Access subscription, which includes
       unlimited access to NYTimes.com.
     * 10. I have an existing IHT digital subscription. Can I also access apps and other products from The New York Times?
       Back to top
       If you have purchased the IHT Smartphone app + NYTimes.com package or the IHT All Digital Access package, you will be given unlimited access to NYTimes.com. To access specific NYTimes
       smartphone or tablet apps, you will need to subscribe to the appropriate New York Times subscription product separately.
       Note, if you have purchased either the IHT Smartphone app + NYTimes.com or the IHT All Digital Access package, you will need to use a different e-mail address for the NYTimes digital
       subscription that you wish to purchase in order to access the NYTimes apps.
     * 11. What is the difference between International Herald Tribune and New York Times apps?
       Back to top
       The International Herald Tribune is the global edition of The New York Times and combines the extensive resources of its own correspondents with those of The Times to give its internationally
       engaged readers a distinctive global perspective on geopolitics, business, sports, culture and more. The IHT apps for iPhone and iPad are refreshed around the clock from the IHT news hubs in
       Hong Kong, Paris and New York and include the latest news from global.nytimes.com.
     * 12. Can I get both NYTimes and IHT apps in one package?
       Back to top
       At this time, it is not possible to purchase one single digital subscription that includes access to both IHT and NYTimes apps. If you wish, for example, to buy both the IHT app for iPad and
       the NYTimes app for iPad, you would need to buy two separate subscriptions. However, IHT Smartphone and All Digital Access packages do include full access to NYTimes.com, as does an
       International Herald Tribune home delivery subscription.
     * 13. Are there any subscription discounts?
       Back to top
       Yes. For a limited time, all new subscribers who sign up through NYTimes.com will receive a special introductory offer.
       Sign up today »
     * 14. Can I still access NYTimes.com articles through Facebook, Twitter, search engines or my blog?
       Back to top
       Yes. We encourage links from Facebook, Twitter, search engines, blogs and other social media. When you visit NYTimes.com through a link from one of these channels, that article (or video,
       slide show, etc.) will count toward your monthly limit of 10 free articles, but you will still be able to view it even if you've already read your 10 free articles.
       Like other external links, links from search engine results will count toward your monthly limit. If you have reached your monthly limit, you'll have a daily limit of five free articles
       through a given search engine. This limit applies to most search engines.
     * 15. I am a home delivery customer. How do I activate my free, unlimited digital access?
       Back to top
       If your home delivery account is already connected to the account you use to read and comment on NYTimes.com, you won't need to do a thing. If not, you'll just need to connect your home
       delivery account to an NYTimes.com account.
       To begin the simple two-step linking process, click the Get started link below. You'll need your home delivery account number and the last name associated with your home delivery account in
       order to link.
       Get started »
     * 16. I am currently an International Herald Tribune home delivery subscriber and have already linked my accounts for my IHT All Digital Access. Do I still have access to the NYTimes apps?
       Back to top
       You may access any unlocked content on NYTimes apps. If you wish to have unlimited access to all content on the NYTimes apps, you will need to purchase a separate subscription using a
       different e-mail address than the one associated with your IHT digital subscription account.
     * 17. Are eReader apps (e.g. IHT for Kindle, IHT for Nook) included in IHT All Digital Access?
       Back to top
       No. eReader apps are not included with any IHT digital subscriptions.
     * 18. I’m not currently a digital subscriber. What kind of content counts toward my monthly limit on NYTimes.com? Do I get access to anything?
       Back to top
       Visitors to NYTimes.com can always browse the home page, as well as all section fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Articles, blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features
       will all count toward the monthly limit of 10 free articles. Note that the monthly limit is based on items, not page views: a multi-page article or slide show counts as one item (or one
       "article view"). Additionally, reader contributions (comments) do not count toward your monthly limit.
       Here are a few examples of "section fronts":
       Politics | Arts | Opinion
       And here are some examples of "blog fronts":
       Well | Bits | City Room
       Upon reaching your monthly reading limit, you'll be asked to subscribe. Your subscription helps us continue to invest in the quality journalism you know and love. But if you don't subscribe,
       your free access will be reset at the beginning of the next month, and you'll once again be able to enjoy our content.
       Also note that IHT apps are free to download and install, and they include a number of sections for free, including Front Page. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections.
       For nonsubscribers, articles from the New York Times archives from 1923 through 1986 are $3.95 each but do not count toward the monthly limit. Views of archived articles outside that date
       range are free but do count toward the 10-article monthly limit.
       Why wait? Sign up today »
     * 19. How do I download the apps that are included with my digital subscription?
       Back to top
       To download IHT smartphone and tablet apps, visit our Downloads page.
     * 20. How do I log in to the IHT apps?
       Back to top
       To log in to an IHT app, go to a section front (e.g. Sports, Views) and tap on any article with a lock symbol next to it. You will be presented with a registration page inviting you to create
       a new account or log in with your existing account. Enter your account details and submit. You will be delivered back to the app where you are now free to browse all content on the app. You
       will not be required to log in again unless you change your account details or reinstall the app on your device.
       If you do not see the registration page by following the steps above, swipe to the next article. The registration page should appear after no more than two or three articles. If it still does
       not appear, you are already logged in to the app.
     * 21. Is there any free content within the IHT apps?
       Back to top
       Both the IHT apps for iPhone and iPad are free to download from iTunes. The following sections are free to access without a paid subscription:
          + IHT app for iPad: Front Page, Videos, Day in Pictures, Cartoons, Business Navigator
          + IHT app for iPhone and Android-power phones: Front Page, Videos, Day in Pictures
     * 22. What is a "section front" or "blog front"?
       Back to top
       Each section of NYTimes.com has a "front page," or a main page of the section. Each blog also has a front or main page, where you can skim partial posts (and sometimes read full posts).

       Section front                                          Blog front
       An example of a section front
       (click image to enlarge or visit this page on the site)
                                                              An example of a blog front
                                                              (click image to enlarge or visit this page on the site)

       If you do not have a subscription, your limited access to NYTimes.com includes these front pages, where you can browse headlines and summaries and read any content that's visible on that
       page. But if you click through to a full article or blog post, the new page will count toward your monthly limit of 10 complimentary articles.
     * 23. How can I keep track of how many articles I have read on NYTimes.com each month?
       Back to top
       When you get close to your monthly limit, pop-up alerts will begin to appear at the bottom of pages you read on NYTimes.com. The alerts will tell you how many free articles remain in the
       current month. Note that the number of "remaining" articles does not include the article you're currently viewing; the current article counts as an "already read" article.
     * 24. If I go back and read an article I’ve already read, will that count toward my monthly limit on NYTimes.com?
       Back to top
       No. If you view an article you have already read in the current month, it will not count again toward your monthly limit.
     * 25. Do comments count toward my monthly limit?
       Back to top
       No. User-generated content does not count toward your monthly limit on NYTimes.com. This includes comments on articles and blog posts.
       When you first read a blog post, it will count toward your 10-article monthly limit. But if you comment on the post or refresh the page to see other readers' comments, it will not count
       again.
       When you click the Comments link on an article page to view the associated readers' comments page, the new page will not count toward your monthly limit (unless there is new Times content on
       the page, which is rare).
     * 26. Can I access my digital subscription on more than one computer, smartphone or tablet?
       Back to top
       Yes, as long as your subscription covers the devices you want to use. You can access NYTimes.com on any browser, on any device. If you have more than one smartphone, you will be able to
       access the IHT app on all your smartphones. You will also have access to the IHT app for iPad on multiple iPad tablets. Note that you must log in on every device to access unlimited content.
       To make sure your subscription covers the applications you want to use, review the subscription packages »
     * 27. How do I change the e-mail address that’s associated with my digital subscription?
       Back to top
       To change your e-mail address, visit the My Account area. In the My Profile section, click the Change link below your e-mail address. Enter a new address, and then click Save.
       If the e-mail address you want to use is already associated with a different NYTimes.com account, an error message will appear. To resolve this, please complete the steps on the Subscription
       E-Mail Address help page. You can also watch a step-by-step video of the process.
       If you're still unable to change your e-mail address, please contact Customer Care.
     * 28. Can I give someone a digital subscription as a gift?
       Back to top
       No. We don't currently offer digital gift subscriptions, but we plan to offer them soon. Please make sure your e-mail address is up-to-date so you can receive the latest news and
       announcements from NYTimes.com.
       In the meantime, you can still give the gift of home delivery of The International Herald Tribune, which includes the IHT All Digital Access package.
     * 29. Do you offer free trial subscriptions?
       Back to top
       Visitors can enjoy 10 free articles each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as unrestricted access to browse the home page, section fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Your free, limited
       access resets every month. We may also announce special offers from time to time, including free trials.
       Also note that IHT apps are free to download and install, and they include the Front Page section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections.
     * 30. I am affiliated with a college or university. Can I get a digital subscription discount?
       Back to top
       No. The IHT does not currently offer digital subscription discounts to students, teachers or administrators.
     * 31. I have a subscription to the IHT on my Kindle, or other e-reader. Does this give me access to NYTimes.com?
       Back to top
       At this time, subscribers to the IHT on Kindle and Nook devices do not receive full access to NYTimes.com. Please make sure your e-mail address is up-to-date so you can receive the latest
       site news and announcements from NYTimes.com.
     * 32. Can I create more than one NYTimes.com account that corresponds to my subscription? Do you offer a “family plan”?
       Back to top
       No. You can create only one account (with one e-mail address and password).
     * 33. I’ve signed up for NYTimes.com e-mail newsletters. Will e-mail newsletters be affected by digital subscriptions?
       Back to top
       No. You don't need a digital subscription in order to subscribe to our e-mail newsletters. Like other external links, e-mail newsletter links to NYTimes.com will count toward your monthly
       limit, but you will still be able to view the linked article even if you've already reached your monthly limit.
     * 34. Will you offer subscription apps on tablets other than the iPad?
       Back to top
       We are evaluating the latest platforms and devices. Please make sure your e-mail address is up-to-date so you can receive the latest site news and announcements from NYTimes.com.
     * 35. My question was not answered here. How can I get more information?
       Back to top
       Please contact Customer Care by calling (877) 206-8027 or by e-mailing IHTHelp@nytimes.com.
       For more information on international calling, visit the International Contact Info page.
     * 36. How do I send you my feedback on digital subscriptions and products?
       Back to top
       We welcome your comments. To send suggestions or comments, please use our feedback form.
       If you're experiencing problems with your digital subscription, please use this form instead

Help

   Help > Managing My Account > E-Mail

E-Mail

     * 1. Why did my NYTimes.com e-mail stop coming?
     * 2. I have junk e-mail filtering or spam blocking software set up; how do I make sure I receive NYTimes.com e-mail?
     * 3. Why would I receive e-mail from NYTimes.com?
     * 4. How do I unsubscribe from NYTimes.com e-mails?
     * 5. I've signed up for NYTimes.com e-mail newsletters. Will e-mail newsletters be affected by digital subscriptions?
     * 6. Can I put a vacation hold on my NYTimes.com e-mail delivery?
     * 7. What does "e-mail format" mean?
     * 8. Why don't the links in my Today's Headlines daily e-mail work?

     * 1. Why did my NYTimes.com e-mail stop coming?
       Back to top
       Several things can affect the delivery of e-mail from NYTimes.com to your Inbox. The two most common reasons are:
          + The e-mail was blocked by your spam filter. Check your Spam, Bulk or Junk folder to see if our messages ended up there.
          + Your e-mail address may have bounced or rejected mail from us at one point, which means that our servers will not send to that address again until further notice. If you believe that
            this might be the case, please contact Customer Service.
       The best way to ensure that NYTimes.com e-mail will reach you is to add the nytimes.com domain to your e-mail address book (or to a safe list or white list, if your e-mail client has one). If
       you can't add the full domain name, you can add the individual e-mail addresses your newsletters are sent from. The main address we send from is nytdirect [at] nytimes.com.
     * 2. I have junk e-mail filtering or spam blocking software set up; how do I make sure I receive NYTimes.com e-mail?
       Back to top
       To ensure that you receive e-mail from NYTimes.com, please do one of the following:
         1. Add the nytimes.com domain to your e-mail address book or to a safe list or white list. If you can't add the full domain name, you can add the individual e-mail addresses your
            newsletters are sent from. The main address we send from is nytdirect [at] nytimes.com.
         2. If your settings don't allow you to add e-mail addresses to a safe list or white list, contact your e-mail/Internet provider's Customer Service for assistance with your configuration
            options.
         3. Disable your junk mail filtering or spam-blocking software.
     * 3. Why would I receive e-mail from NYTimes.com?
       Back to top
       Here are the main reasons why NYTimes.com will send you an e-mail:
          + You have signed up for our free e-mail services, such as Today's Headlines, DealBook, TicketWatch, etc. For a complete list see: www.nytimes.com/email
          + You have a digital subscription or a subscription to Crosswords or another product.
          + You have requested your password be reset through our Password Reset utility.
          + You have purchased something on our Web site, so we've sent you a purchase confirmation e-mail.
          + You have contacted Customer Service regarding a question or issue.
          + NYTimes.com may occasionally send notifications to registered users about major changes to our site or our Privacy Policy.
     * 4. How do I unsubscribe from NYTimes.com e-mails?
       Back to top
       To stop or suspend delivery of the Today's Headlines, visit our E-Mail Preferences page. You can also unsubscribe from occasional e-mails about new features and special offers on the same
       page. For further assistance in unsubscribing, contact Customer Service.
     * 5. I've signed up for NYTimes.com e-mail newsletters. Will e-mail newsletters be affected by digital subscriptions?
       Back to top
       No. You don't need a digital subscription in order to subscribe to our e-mail newsletters. Like other external links, e-mail newsletter links to NYTimes.com will count toward your monthly
       limit, but you will still be able to view the linked article even if you've already reached your monthly limit.
       See also Can I still access NYTimes.com articles through Facebook, Twitter, search engines or my blog?
     * 6. Can I put a vacation hold on my NYTimes.com e-mail delivery?
       Back to top
       Currently, we do not offer a suspension or vacation hold feature for our e-mail services. You can always cancel or activate the delivery of e-mail updates at: www.nytimes.com/email
     * 7. What does "e-mail format" mean?
       Back to top
       When you sign up for NYTimes.com e-mail, you can select HTML or Text. If you're using an older computer or certain mobile devices, you may want to select Text to ensure that you can read our
       messages. Otherwise, select HTML to get the most out your e-mail newsletter subscriptions.
       If you choose to receive e-mail in HTML format, please keep in mind that the client or browser you use to read your messages may affect how images are loaded. If images are not loading, check
       for an option to display external images or show images.
     * 8. Why don't the links in my Today's Headlines daily e-mail work?
       Back to top
       If the links in your Today's Headlines e-mail are broken, your e-mail program is probably incompatible with the HTML version of the mailings. Please change the format to Text only.

THE_TITLE:Crosswords - The New York Times
   #RSS

   Edition: U.S. / Global

Help

   Help > Games > Crosswords

Crosswords

   1. What are the features of NYTimes.com’s Premium Crosswords?
   2. What are the NYTimes.com Terms of Service and Privacy Policy?
   3. How do I contact Customer Service for Premium Crosswords?

   Gameplay
   4. When can I get today's puzzle?
   5. How do I print a crossword puzzle?
   6. How do I download a crossword puzzle as a PDF?
   7. Can I print an answer key for the current crossword puzzle?
   8. How do I get the solution for a puzzle?
   9. Can I erase letters on the puzzle I'm playing?
   10. How do I switch between my selection between Across and Down?
   11. What is the difference between entering an answer in pen or pencil?
   12. Are puzzles solved in "Play for fun" mode eligible for the Top Ten Puzzlers list?
   13. What are the available keyboard shortcuts?

   Subscription and Purchasing Info
   14. How much does it cost to subscribe to Premium Crosswords?
   15. How do I cancel my Premium Crosswords subscription?
   16. What is the refund policy for Premium Crosswords?
   17. Will my Premium Crosswords subscription be renewed automatically?
   18. Can I give someone Premium Crosswords as a gift?
   19. I am a digital subscriber — are Premium Crosswords included in my subscription?
   20. How do I make a purchase on NYTimes.com?
   21. How can I access digital products that I have already purchased?
   22. I'm a Premium Crosswords subscriber. Can I also access New York Times crosswords on my mobile device?

   Troubleshooting and Support
   23. How do I print a puzzle?
   24. Why can’t I print a crossword puzzle?
   25. Why can’t I print the Sunday puzzle on a single page?
   26. How do I save the puzzle as a PDF?
   27. Can I still solve puzzles using Across Lite?
   28. Is The New York Times no longer supporting Across Lite?
   29. How do I print a puzzle in Across Lite?
   30. I can’t save my answers for a puzzle I’ve been working on — are you planning on adding the ability to save?
   31. Where is the Cartoon section?
   32. Where are the Bridge and Chess sections?
   33. What if I still have questions about these crosswords issues?

   1. What are the features of NYTimes.com’s Premium Crosswords?

   You can download and play the New York Times Daily Crossword Puzzle on your computer or play the puzzle online. You can also print out the puzzle and take it with you wherever you go.

   The service also features:
     * Exclusive online access to the daily New York Times Crossword Puzzles as they appear in our newspaper
     * All Sunday magazine puzzles, including the acrostics, online
     * Web-only monthly bonus puzzles
     * A puzzle archive going back to 1996
     * The ability to download the daily puzzle as a PDF
     * Across Lite, a Web browser plug-in that lets you play puzzles on your computer
     * Time how long it takes you to solve today's puzzle and see how you stack up against other puzzlers
     * Collaborate in real time with other members to solve today's puzzle
     * Solve classic puzzles head-to-head with our Challenge Matches feature

   Please see How to Play the Online Puzzles for more helpful information on the many puzzle features. For further information on downloading Across Lite and about its features, see our Across Lite
   FAQ.

   2. What are the NYTimes.com Terms of Service and Privacy Policy?

   NYTimes.com respects your privacy. We will never share any personal information without your consent. Please read our Privacy Policy and Terms of Service.

   3. How do I contact Customer Service for Premium Crosswords?

   Puzzled by today's puzzle? Visit the Wordplay blog for discussion about the day's challenge.

   If you have any additional questions about our Premium Crosswords service, please contact us.

Gameplay

   This section contains information on how to play crosswords using the "Play for fun" mode. For information on "Play against the clock," "Solve with a friend" and Across Lite gameplay, see How to
   Play Online Puzzles.

   4. When can I get today's puzzle?

   The current day's puzzle becomes available at 10 p.m. Eastern Time the night before. For example, Tuesday's puzzle becomes available at 10 p.m. Eastern Time Monday. On weekends, the puzzle is
   available earlier — at 6 p.m. Eastern Time on Saturday and Sunday.

   5. How do I print a crossword puzzle?

   In "Play for fun" mode, there is an option to print the current puzzle. You can print a copy of the puzzle with no answers filled in, with all of the answers filled in or with just the answers
   you have filled in so far.

   See also How do I download a crossword puzzle as a PDF?

   6. How do I download a crossword puzzle as a PDF?

   In "Play for fun" mode, there is an option to print the current puzzle. After selecting what to print (your answers filled in, all answers filled in or a blank puzzle) a print menu will appear;
   you can choose to Print to PDF (or a similar command, the exact wording depends on your operating system). Selecting Print to PDF will create a PDF of the puzzle. The Adobe Web site has more
   information on creating a PDF from the print menu.

   7. Can I print an answer key for the current crossword puzzle?

   Yes. In "Play for fun" mode, there is an option to print the current puzzle. From the print menu that appears, you can choose to print the puzzle With Complete Solution to have all of the answers
   filled in when you print out the puzzle.

   8. How do I get the solution for a puzzle?

   Puzzle solutions are available immediately. You can choose to reveal the correct letters certain squares or check the answers for squares you have already filled in. Reveal shows you the answer,
   Check just shows whether the answer you have entered is correct, without showing you the correct answer; if the entry is incorrect, the incorrect letters will appear in red.

   From the Reveal drop-down menu, you can select to reveal the following:
     * Current square reveals the correct entry for the currently selected square
     * Current word reveals the correct word for the currently selected entry
     * Entire grid reveals the answers to the entire puzzle
     * Incorrect squares reveals the answers to all incorrect squares in the entire puzzle
     * Selection reveals the correct answer to all of the currently selected squares

   From the Check drop-down menu, you can mark incorrect letters in red. You can select the following options:
     * Current square checks if the currently selected square contains the correct letter
     * Current word checks if the entry for the currently selected word is correct
     * Entire grid checks if the entire puzzle is correct
     * Selection checks if the currently selected squares contain the correct letters

   See also Can I print an answer key for the current crossword puzzle?

   9. Can I erase letters on the puzzle I'm playing?

   Yes. From the Clear drop-down menu, you can select to clear the following:
     * Current square removes the letter from the currently selected square
     * Current word removes the letters from the currently word
     * Entire grid removes all of the answers from the puzzle
     * Selection removes the letters from the currently selected squares

   10. How do I switch between my selection between Across and Down?

   You can change the direction of your selection by double-clicking a square. You can also use your keyboard to change directions.

   11. What is the difference between entering an answer in pen or pencil?

   Answers will be in a lighter font if they are added in pencil mode. This is so you can provide yourself with visual cues if you aren't sure about an answer. Checking or revealing an entry still
   functions the same way, whether you entered the answer in pen or pencil.

   12. Are puzzles solved in "Play for fun" mode eligible for the Top Ten Puzzlers list?

   No. We provide a timer for personal use, so you can keep track of how quickly you're solving a puzzle. In order to be ranked on the Top Ten Puzzlers list, you must use the Play Against the Clock
   applet to solve today's puzzle.

   13. What are the available keyboard shortcuts?

   You can use the following keyboard shortcuts

   Tab
   Moves to the next clue in current direction.
   When you are at the last clue in the current direction, you will be taken to the first clue in the opposite direction.

   Enter/Return
   Moves to the next clue in current direction.
   When you are at the last clue in the current direction, you will be taken to the first clue in the opposite direction.

   Down arrow
   Moves down one square.
   Selecting Shift + Down moves your selection to next down clue if the current direction is down; if the current direction is across, the next row in the solution grid is selected.

   Up
   Moves up one square.
   Selecting Shift + Up moves your selection in the current direction.

   Left
   Moves left one square.
   Selecting Shift + Left moves your selection to next clue to the left.

   Right
   Moves right one square.
   Selecting Shift + Right moves your selection to next clue to the right.

   Delete
   Deletes a letter from the squares associated with the selected word. If the current direction is across, your selection will move to the left; if the current direction is down, your selection
   will move up.

Subscription and Purchasing Info

   14. How much does it cost to subscribe to Premium Crosswords?

   We have two purchase options:
     * Annual subscription: $39.95, plus tax (United States and Canada); $47.94 (International)
     * Monthly subscription: $6.95, plus tax (United States and Canada); $8.34 (International)

   15. How do I cancel my Premium Crosswords subscription?

   You can cancel your subscription by calling Customer Care at (800) 591-9233.

   View the full NYTimes cancellation and refund policy »

   16. What is the refund policy for Premium Crosswords?

   For details about refunds, please review our Terms of Sale.

   To cancel your Premium Crosswords subscription, call Customer Care at (800) 591-9233.

   17. Will my Premium Crosswords subscription be renewed automatically?

   Yes. Both the annual and the monthly Premium Crosswords subscriptions renew automatically. Provided that your current e-mail address is in our system, a reminder e-mail with cancellation
   instructions will be sent to you one week before the subscription is scheduled to renew. To check that your e-mail address is current, please visit the My Account area of NYTimes.com.

   To prevent interruptions to your service, we also suggest that you verify your credit card information is current in your Purchase History.

   18. Can I give someone Premium Crosswords as a gift?

   Yes, you can give a one-year gift subscription to Premium Crosswords. Please visit our gift subscription page. Note that gift subscriptions of Premium Crosswords are nonrefundable.

   19. I am a digital subscriber — are Premium Crosswords included in my subscription?

   No. Premium Crossword subscriptions and digital subscriptions are separate. However, all Times subscribers (home delivery and digital) get 50 percent off Premium Crosswords subscriptions.

   For more information, visit the My Account area of NYTimes.com.

   20. How do I make a purchase on NYTimes.com?

   You can purchase digital products from NYTimes.com quickly and securely. When you make your first purchase on NYTimes.com, you will be asked to provide billing and credit card information over a
   secure connection. We accept American Express, Visa, MasterCard and Discover Card. Once you have completed this process, you will not need to re-enter this information for subsequent
   transactions. You can update and modify all of your billing and credit card information in the secured account management area in your Purchase History.

   21. How can I access digital products that I have already purchased?

   You can access active NYTimes.com digital products by visiting your Purchase History in the My Account area. You can always get quick access to the My Account area by clicking your user name in
   the top right corner of almost any NYTimes.com page.

   22. I'm a Premium Crosswords subscriber. Can I also access New York Times crosswords on my mobile device?

   Our mobile crossword apps are currently developed in partnership with external companies, which means their billing must be handled separately from online crosswords subscriptions. In the future,
   we hope to combine these subscriptions, but you must currently subscribe to mobile crosswords separately.

Troubleshooting and Support

   23. How do I print a puzzle?

   Click the Play button and then click Print Puzzle from the pop-up menu that appears.

   For Today’s Puzzle, you can click Print Puzzle.

   For the Latest Puzzles, you can click the printer icon.

   You can also print a puzzle using Across Lite. For more information, see How do I print a puzzle in Across Lite?

   24. Why can’t I print a crossword puzzle?

   To print a puzzle, follow the instructions in How do I print a puzzle?

   If you’re still having trouble, your browser may be incompatible with the print feature.

   If you’re using Internet Explorer 7 or 8:
   We’re working on bringing the ability to print to these versions of Internet Explorer. In the meantime, you can upgrade to Internet Explorer 9, or use a different browser like Chrome or Firefox.

   How to check your version of Internet Explorer »

   If you’re using Google Chrome:
   You may need to update your browser to the latest version. See this Google help page for more information.

   You can also print a puzzle using Across Lite. For more information, see How do I print a puzzle in Across Lite?

   25. Why can’t I print the Sunday puzzle on a single page?

   We’re currently working on fitting all clues for the Sunday crossword on a single page. In the meantime, you can print the puzzle using Across Lite. For more information, see How do I print a
   puzzle in Across Lite?

   26. How do I save the puzzle as a PDF?

   Go to the crossword archives and click the PDF link for the puzzle you wish to save.

   27. Can I still solve puzzles using Across Lite?

   Yes. Click the Play button and then click Download for Play on Across Lite from the pop-up menu that appears.

   More information on using Across Lite »

   28. Is The New York Times no longer supporting Across Lite?

   You can still use Across Lite to solve New York Times puzzles. We appreciate solvers' devotion to Across Lite and, while we want to offer more choices to our solvers, The New York Times does not
   have any plans to stop supporting Across Lite gameplay.

   29. How do I print a puzzle in Across Lite?

   Open the puzzle in Across Lite and then select the Print button from the top toolbar.

   For more information on solving puzzles using Across Lite, see Can I still solve puzzles using Across Lite?

   30. I can’t save my answers for a puzzle I’ve been working on — are you planning on adding the ability to save?

   Yes. We will continue to add features to our new crosswords gameplay, and saving and resuming play is a feature we are planning to add soon.

   31. Where is the Cartoon section?

   The Cartoon section has been temporarily moved to our Wordplay blog. You can access cartoons directly at wordplay.blogs.nytimes.com/cartoons.

   32. How do I access the Bridge and Chess sections?

   The Bridge and Chess columns are available on the Puzzle Page under the heading More in Games.

   You can also find them by visiting our topic pages:

   topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/subjects/b/bridge_card_game/index.html

   topics.nytimes.com/topics/reference/timestopics/subjects/c/chess/index.html

   33. What if I still have questions about these crosswords issues?

   You can contact us by e-mailing crosswords@nytimes.com.

Help

   Help > Games > How to Play the Online Puzzles

How to Play the Online Puzzles

   Welcome! Please take a moment to learn all about NYTimes.com's Premium Crosswords. First, please add the Premium Crosswords page to your bookmarks or favorites list for quick access to New York
   Times puzzles. And don't forget the Crosswords FAQ, which is loaded with useful information to help you get the most out of your Premium Crosswords subscription.

   Select one of the following topics to learn more:

Today's Crossword Puzzle

   Today's Puzzle (Across Lite)
   Play Against the Clock (Java applet)
   Play With a Friend (Java applet)

Classic Puzzle

   Challenge Matches (Java applet)

Additional Information

   Crossword Puzzle Archives
   About the Top Ten Puzzlers
   More Help

Today's Crossword Puzzle

   There are three ways that you can solve today's crossword puzzle.

Today's Puzzle (Across Lite or PDF)

   This is the basic crossword puzzle. Play online or print it to solve with pencil (or pen!) and paper.

   You'll need to download and install the free Across Lite puzzle software in order to access the puzzles online. You can also download the puzzle as a PDF for offline viewing.

   The current day's puzzle becomes available at 10 p.m. Eastern time the night before. For example, Tuesday's puzzle becomes available at 10 p.m. Eastern time Monday. On weekends, the puzzle is
   available earlier — at 6 p.m. Eastern time on Saturday and Sunday.

   To learn more about the features of Across Lite and for instructions on how to download it, see our Across Lite FAQ.

   How does the Crosswords Answer Key work?

Play Against the Clock (Java applet)

   Time yourself as you solve today's puzzle and see how you stack up against other Premium Crosswords members!

   In order to become a Top Ten Puzzler, you must use Play Against the Clock (Java applet).

   After launching the Play Against the Clock applet, you'll need to click OK to start the clock.

   Once you've successfully solved the puzzle, click the Submit Solution button at the top of the page.

   Please note that you cannot submit an incorrect solution, nor can you pause the clock.

   Note: Please do not select Play Against the Clock if you wish to enter a solution that you have solved already. Your solving time will be falsely low and will spoil for the fun for others in the
   Top Ten Puzzlers applet.

Play With a Friend (Java applet)

   Collaborate in real time to solve today's puzzle with another Premium Crosswords Member! Every letter you type will also appear in your friend's grid. You can also chat at the same time,
   discussing clues and solutions, or whatever you like.

   There are two ways to start Play With a Friend. You can either let us pair you with a random solving partner or you can create your own room and coordinate with another member to enter it.

   Automatic Pairing
    1. Click where it says Click Here to Add Your Name.
    2. Your member name will then be displayed along with other members looking for a solving partner.
    3. At this point, you can either click on another member's name to automatically create a room or you can click on a room to join a puzzle in the process of being solved.
    4. If you close your browser window or leave the puzzle page, your name will be removed from the list of puzzlers.

   Create a Room
    1. Enter the name of a room in the box on the right. Example: stamford
    2. Then choose whether your room will be public or private.
       - A public room means that other members will be able to enter your room and solve along with you. Public rooms will be displayed in green to other users.
       - A private room will require you to enter a password. Your puzzle partner will then need to enter this password to join your room. Private rooms will be displayed in red to other users.
    3. Coordinate with a member to enter the same room name into the box below at the same time. For instance, if you made an appointment with a friend to start puzzling in room 'stamford' at 2 p.m.
       Then, at 2 p.m. you must both enter stamford as the room. If your friend did the same, you will be connected and can start solving and chatting together.
       Tip: Use e-mail, instant messenger or the phone to coordinate the names of rooms and times that you will solve the puzzle with your friends.

   Note:
     * Each member will have their own color for the letters that they enter.
     * Up to five members can simultaneously solve a puzzle at the same time in the same room.
     * If a member exits the room, the letters that they had entered will turn to black.

   The Play With a Friend applet has a built-in chat window so you can talk to your friends at the same time that you are solving puzzles to discuss clues, possible solutions or whatever you like.
   In order to chat you must first enter a room by creating a room in the Play With a Friend applet. Once you have created and entered a room simply enter text where it says Enter text to chat. You
   can either press ENTER on your keyboard or click the SEND button on your screen to post your message.

Classic Puzzle

Challenge Matches (Java applet)

   This feature allows you to compete head-to-head against other members. Points will be awarded based on the number of correct letters entered.

   Which puzzles are used for the Challenge Matches?
   The puzzles used for the Challenge Matches are New York Times puzzles selected at random from our archives, 1996 through 2002.

   We have chosen to display the day of the week for each puzzle, but not the date of publication. The day is meant to define the degree of difficulty with Monday being the easiest and Saturday
   being the hardest. Sunday puzzles are not included in Challenge Matches.

   How do I find others to challenge?
   To begin a Challenge Match, click on a member's name at the right, and the other player will be contacted to accept the challenge. Both you and the other player must click OK to begin loading the
   game. If no name or room is listed, add your name or create a room for others to select. If you would like to play alone in Single Player Mode, please create a room and select Single Player.

   How does accept challenge work?
   Upon request for a challenge match, both players are prompted to click OK to begin the game. Once both players have clicked OK the game begins loading.

   How does the scoring work?
     * Letters that are entered correctly are worth 1 point and cannot be overwritten by your opponent.
     * Letters entered incorrectly will result in the deduction of one point and may be overwritten by either player.
     * Incorrect letters are marked with a red dot.
     * A letter is first entered in a lighter color while the information is being passed to the server. The server processes it, adjusts the scores and sends it as official entry to all players.
       After receiving it, the letter sets in a darker shade and the score is official.
     * If you enter a letter in your color, it may change immediately into your opponents color. This may happen when your opponent entered the same letter a fraction of a second earlier and his
       entry was received earlier on the server than your entry.
     * If you leave a room before the puzzle is completely solved, your opponent will be declared the winner.

   What does "Another Puzzle" do?
   The Another Puzzle option on the top of the Challenge Match game grid allows one player to request a new puzzle to the other. The opponent has the right to accept or refuse the new puzzle
   request. The opponent may select OK to begin a new puzzle, or click Refuse to return to the game in play.

Additional Information

Crossword Puzzle Archives

   You can access crosswords from as far back as 1996 in the puzzle archives. You can play puzzles online with the Across Lite puzzle software or download puzzles as PDF files. To access the
   archive, you must be signed in. Go to the Puzzle Archive page or the Crossword Puzzle Archive section on the far right of the Premium Crosswords page.

   Please note, only puzzles from April 1, 2011 or later are available as PDF files.

About the Top Ten Puzzlers

   The Top Ten Puzzlers applet provides a way for Premium Crossword members to determine just how good a puzzler they really are.

   In order to be ranked among the Top Ten Puzzlers list, you must use the Play Against The Clock applet to solve today's puzzle.

   Upon successfully completing and then submitting the solution, your time will be displayed in the Top Ten Puzzlers applet.

   How do you calculate the Top Ten Puzzlers?
   There are three times that we are capturing: the Most Recent Ten Solvers, the First Ten Solvers, and the Fastest Ten Solvers.

   Most Recent Ten Solvers
   The Most Recent Ten Solvers will display the ten Premium Crossword Members who have most recently solved today's puzzle.

   The First Ten Solvers
   In order to be included on the First Ten Puzzlers list, you must be one of the first 10 members to correctly complete and submit today's puzzle. A new puzzle is published each night at 10 p.m.
   Eastern Time, 6 p.m. on weekends (Saturday and Sunday).

   Fastest Ten Solvers
   The Fastest Ten Solvers list displays the solving times of the ten members to most quickly complete and submit today's puzzle.

   How are the Week, Month and Year tabs calculated?
   The Week, Month and Year rankings are calculated by awarding points to the Top Ten Puzzlers.

   At the end of the each day points will be awarded for the First Ten Solvers and the Fastest Ten Solvers. The week, month and year tabs display the aggregate scores of the period selected.

   Note: Play Against the Clock and Top Ten Puzzlers are strictly for fun, and should not be perceived as an authoritative ranking.

   We understand that users may first solve the puzzle in either the newspaper or Across Lite and then enter the Play Against the Clock applet.

More Help

   Need more help? Please contact us.

   Not a member? Subscribe now.
