Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

     * Contact Us
     * Help

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

   Property Of Beautiful Custom Home with Magnificent Views Property Of Beautiful Custom Home with Magnificent Views Property Of Beautiful Custom Home with Magnificent Views

About This Property

   Located in Hidden Oaks and built to capture the beautiful views of the mountains and valley, this fantastic custom home is the perfect opportunity for someone looking to enjoy all the creature
   comforts living in luxury has to offer. A great room with gorgeous views and large deck, a main floor master suite with jetted tub and steam shower, a gourmet kitchen, a walk out lower level with
   cozy family room, a wet bar and conditioned wine room, a game room built to impress, an exercise room and kids play area are just some of the benefits you'll enjoy in this wonderful home.

   View more information about this property Summit Sotheby's International Realty

Customer Service

NYTimes.com

   Need to contact someone about our Web site? Make sure you've read our help and FAQs.
     * For general help questions, please use our help form.
     * For questions about digital subscriptions, crosswords or other paid products, please see the Help With Online Paid Products page.
     * For a possible correction, or to reach the Web site's editorial staff, you can send an e-mail.

Delivery or Print Subscription Issues

     * Place orders, temporarily stop service or inquire about billing or service by calling 1‑800‑NYTIMES (1‑800‑698‑4637), by sending an e-mail or by visiting homedelivery.nytimes.com.
     * Send an e-mail to the Sr. V.P. of Circulation.

International Herald Tribune

     * Advertisers, please call (212) 556‑7194 or send an e-mail.
     * For subscription inquiries, please visit subs.iht.com or send an e-mail.

Contact Someone at the Newspaper

Editorial

     * Send a Letter to the Editor.
     * Submit an Op-Ed.
     * Submit an Opinion Video.

News Departments and Reporters

     * To send comments and suggestions (about news coverage only) or to report errors that call for a correction, e-mail us or leave a message at 1‑888‑NYT‑NEWS (1‑888‑698‑6397).
     * Most reporters can be reached directly by clicking the byline of any article by that reporter. This will take you to the reporter's Times Topics page, where you can click the Send an E-Mail
       to... link to access the contact form. You can also find most reporters' Times Topics page here (listings are alphabetized by last name; reporters' names are italicized).
     * The Newsroom
       News Tips | The Arts | Business Day | The Foreign Desk | The Metro Desk | The National Desk | Sports | The Washington Bureau
     * The Editors
       The Executive Editor
       The Managing Editor

Public Editor

   Margaret Sullivan, our public editor, represents our readers. You can reach her by e-mail.

Write to the Publisher or General Manager

     * Send an e-mail to Arthur Sulzberger Jr., Chairman & Publisher.
     * Send an e-mail to Denise Warren, General Manager of NYTimes.com.

Call The New York Times From International Locations

   To contact The New York Times by telephone from outside the United States, review the information provided here.

Advertise With The Times

     * For the print reservations procedure and material requirements visit our Self-Service Advertising Portal or call (212) 556-7777.
     * For information about advertising on NYTimes.com, visit nytmediakit.com.
     * Send an e-mail to the Sr. V.P. of Advertising.

Listings: Classifieds, Notices, and Announcements

     * To place a classified ad, death notice or other listing, go to www.nytimes.com/ref/classifieds/.
     * For information about classified advertising, visit advertising.nytimes.com/classified or call 1‑800‑AD‑TIMES (1‑800‑238‑4637).

Wedding/Celebration Announcements

     * For information about submitting a wedding or celebration announcement, or to submit an announcement, visit listings.nytimes.com/Weddings. If you have additional questions, you can also
       e-mail us or call (212) 556‑7325.
     * To obtain a high-quality reprint of a wedding or celebration announcement that appeared in the Times, please call PARS International at (212) 221‑9595, extension 210, or visit
       www.nytreprints.com to order online.

Purchase NYTimes Products

     * For information on The New York Times Replica Edition go here.
     * For information regarding the The Times Digest and the Evening Digest, please call us at (212) 556‑1200, or e-mail us at timesdigest@nytimes.com, or visit www.timesdigest.com.
     * To order The New York Times Large Print Weekly from the past week's Times (including the crossword), call (800) 631‑2580.
     * For photographs, books, commemorative sections and Times merchandise, visit www.nytstore.com.

Education Initiatives of The New York Times

   The New York Times in Education: Educators can order The Times for classroom use at a reduced rate. For more information, teaching resources and programs for K-12 classrooms, visit
   NYTimes.com/nie, call (800) 631‑1222 or send an e-mail to schools@nytimes.com.

   The New York Times in College: Our program for higher education includes reduced rates for home delivery to college students and faculty, a newspaper readership program, teaching strategies for
   using The Times in the college classroom and more. For more information, visit NYTimes.com/edu.

   The New York Times Learning Network: Visit learning.blogs.nytimes.com, a blog about teaching and learning with The Times. The blog contains lesson plans linked to Times articles, as well as a
   daily Student Opinion question, news quiz and much more.

   The New York Times Knowledge Network: The New York Times is working with select educational institutions nationwide to develop unique online courses and programs. Visit NYTimes.com/knownow for
   course offerings.

   Donations: Support the classroom programs of The New York Times in Education by providing The Times to schools in two ways:

   Vacation Donation: home delivery subscribers can donate the credit for their suspended papers when they go on vacation. Call 1‑800‑NYTIMES (1‑800‑698‑4637) or log in to your account at
   homedelivery.nytimes.com.

   Education Donation: individuals may support our program with a credit card donation. Visit NYTimes.com/EducationDonation.

   Click here to learn about the other education initiatives of The New York Times.

   (866) 776-3698 for colleges and universities

Help

   Help > Using NYTimes.com > Editorial Concerns > How to Submit an Opinion Video

How to Submit an Opinion Video

   About Op-Docs:
   Op-Docs is a series of short, opinionated documentaries, produced with wide creative latitude and a range of artistic styles, about current affairs, contemporary life and historical subjects.
   Documentary submissions by both renowned and emerging independent filmmakers and artists are welcome. Join the conversation on Twitter with #nytopdocs.

   Read more about Op-Docs »

   About Op-Ed Videos:
   We also accept submissions of Op-Ed videos that present a clearly articulated argument or viewpoint like a traditional Op-Ed essay and relate to topics in the news.

   In addition to completed videos, we will consider written pitches along with links to representative footage. We cannot consider film trailers, nor can we consider videos that have already been
   posted online or broadcast on television. In addition to new short works, we can consider pieces that are adapted from longer, topical works-in-progress. Submissions should be no more than five
   minutes long.

   Please e-mail submissions to: opinion.video@nytimes.com

   In addition, DVD screeners can be mailed to the editorial department but will not be returned:

   Jason Spingarn-Koff
   Video Journalist
   Editorial Department
   The New York Times
   620 Eighth Avenue
   New York, N.Y. 10018

About Op-Docs

   From left to right: Victor J. Blue for The New York Times; Errol Morris; Courtesy of the Nixon Archives

   Stills, from left to right, "The Role of Youth" by Matt Wolf and Jon Savage, "The Umbrella Man" by Errol Morris and "The Silent Majority" by Penny Lane and Brian L. Frye.

   Op-Docs is The New York Times editorial department’s forum for short, opinionated documentaries, produced with wide creative latitude and a range of artistic styles, covering current affairs,
   contemporary life and historical subjects.
   Op-Doc

     * View Related Videos »
     * How to Submit an Opinion Video »
     * Subscribe to the Op-Docs Feed »
     * Join @nytopinion on Twitter »

   Opinion Twitter Logo.

Connect With Us on Twitter

   For Op-Ed, follow @nytopinion and to hear from the editorial page editor, Andrew Rosenthal, follow @andyrNYT.

   Op-Docs videos are produced by both renowned and emerging filmmakers who express their views in the first person, through their subjects or more subtly through an artistic approach to a topic.
   Each is accompanied by a director’s statement.

   In December 2012, we started a new Op-Docs feature: Scenes.  This is a platform for very short work — snippets of street life, brief observations and interviews, clips from experimental and
   artistic nonfiction videos — that follow less traditional documentary narrative conventions.

   Join the conversation on Twitter with the hashtag #nytopdocs. Also, follow the Op-Docs series’ producer and curator, Jason Spingarn-Koff (@jskoff), and @nytopinion on Twitter for updates. You may
   also e-mail your comments or queries to opinion.video@nytimes.com.

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

See the world differently with the International Herald Tribune

   The IHT combines the extensive international reporting of The Times with the IHT’s distinctive, sophisticated perspective on what’s happening around the world and what it means. Subscribe today
   to the IHT Smartphone or All Digital Access packages for full access to IHT apps and NYTimes.com. IHT All Digital Access also includes the IHT app for iPad with more than 18 international
   sections fully refreshed for Europe and Asia mornings, plus the latest news from global.nytimes.com, videos, Day in Pictures, and extras like cartoons and business travel guides.
   International Herald Tribune
   International Herald Tribune

Frequently Asked Questions

   Back to Top

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?To get unlimited access to IHT apps, you’ll now need a subscription. When you subscribe to the IHT Smartphone or All Digital Access
   packages you’ll also get unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site and mobile site including 100 Archive articles every four weeks. IHT digital subscriptions do not include e-reader editions
   or any New York Times-branded smartphone or tablet apps.

   What is the difference between International Herald Tribune and New York Times apps?The International Herald Tribune is the global edition of The New York Times and combines the extensive
   resources of its own correspondents with those of The Times to give its internationally engaged readers a distinctive global perspective on geopolitics, business, sports, culture and more. The
   IHT apps for smartphones and the iPad are refreshed for Europe and Asia mornings from the IHT news hubs in Hong Kong, Paris and New York and include the latest news from global.nytimes.com.
   International Herald Tribune Users

   Can I get apps from both the IHT and NYT in one package?At this time, it is not possible to purchase one single digital subscription that includes access to both IHT and NYT apps. If you wish,
   for example, to buy both the IHT app for iPad and the NYTimes app for iPad, you would need to buy two separate subscriptions. However, IHT Smartphone and All Digital Access packages do include
   full access to NYTimes.com, as does the IHT home delivery subscription.
   International Herald Tribune Users

   I get home delivery of the IHT newspaper. Do I get free access?Yes. Paid home delivery subscribers to the International Herald Tribune who purchase at least five days per week get a free IHT All
   Digital Access subscription, which includes full access to the IHT apps for iPhone, Android and iPad, plus full access to NYTimes.com on any device.

   In some countries, home delivery of the newspaper is provided by a local partner or franchise, rather than by the International Herald Tribune directly. In most cases, customers in these
   countries will also be able to obtain free access to the IHT All Digital Access package. Please check with your local customer service office for more information.

   To activate your digital subscription to the International Herald Tribune, click here.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?You can cancel your IHT digital subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing
   cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterwards, you will still be able to view 10 articles per month on NYTimes.com and
   read unlocked articles on our apps at no charge, just like any other visitor.

   View the full cancellation and refund policy »

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?All visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar
   month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100
   Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that both NYTimes and IHT apps are free to download and install, and offer a limited number of articles for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to
   all articles, multimedia and tools within the apps.

   View our complete FAQ »

The Global Edition

   Combining the international reporting of The New York Times and the International Herald Tribune, the Global Edition gives readers a 24/7 flow of political, business, opinion, sports, style and
   culture coverage from a distinctly global perspective.

IHT Smartphone Apps

   Get the IHT’s full package of world news, business, culture, style, sports and views articles delivered into the palm of your hand with our easy to navigate apps for iPhone and Android-powered
   phones. Check what’s making the front page, follow breaking stories from global.nytimes.com, browse the Day in Pictures and video galleries, share articles and create your own favorites section.
   Essential world news apps for global thinkers.
   Tablets
   Back to Top

IHT Tablet App

   A distinctive international offering of world news, business, culture, style, sports and opinion from the IHT’s news hubs in Hong Kong, Paris and New York. With more than 18 international
   sections fully refreshed for the Europe and Asia mornings and the latest news feed from global.nytimes.com, the IHT’s app for iPad keeps you abreast of what’s happening in the world and what it
   means, wherever you are.

   Additional features include: videos, Day in Pictures, world weather tool, article sharing, daily cartoons and business travel guides for India, China and the Middle East.

The world’s premier news site.

   Enjoy unlimited access to the world’s finest journalism, with continuous coverage of the most important news, issues and newsmakers, plus provocative opinion and innovative multimedia.
   Video

24-Hour News Desk

   The New York Times newsroom is a 24-hour operation, with journalists in New York, across the nation and around the world reporting on critical events as they unfold.
   Blogs

Videos

   On a wide array of topics — from top news to new films to the latest technology — our videos capture events, issues and newsmakers, from the unique perspectives of renowned Times journalists.
   Multimedia

Multimedia

   From interactive maps to timelines and slide shows, our dynamic multimedia bring out vital aspects of stories in new and compelling ways.
   Podcasts

Blogs

   Over 50 in all, on technology, culture, health and more. Get a financial edge with DealBook; gain political insights with The Caucus; tap the minds of experts in every field.
   Podcasts

The Global Edition

   Combining the international reporting of The New York Times and the International Herald Tribune, the Global Edition gives readers a 24/7 flow of political, business, opinion, sports, style and
   culture coverage from a distinctly global perspective.
   Smartphones
   Back to Top

IHT Smartphone Apps

   Get the IHT’s full package of world news, business, culture, style, sports and views articles delivered into the palm of your hand with our easy to navigate apps for iPhone and Android-powered
   phones. Check what’s making the front page, follow breaking stories from global.nytimes.com, browse the Day in Pictures and video galleries, share articles and create your own favorites section.
   Essential world news apps for global thinkers.
   Tablets
   Back to Top

IHT Tablet App

   A distinctive international offering of world news, business, culture, style, sports and opinion from the IHT’s news hubs in Hong Kong, Paris and New York. With more than 18 international
   sections fully refreshed for the Europe and Asia mornings and the latest news feed from global.nytimes.com, the IHT’s app for iPad keeps you abreast of what’s happening in the world and what it
   means, wherever you are.

   Additional features include: videos, Day in Pictures, world weather tool, article sharing, daily cartoons and business travel guides for India, China and the Middle East.
   Home Delivery Back to Top

Home Delivery + Free IHT All Digital Access

The convenience of home delivery and so much more.

   A home delivery subscription to the International Herald Tribune now includes unlimited free access to the IHT apps for iPhone and Android-powered phones, the IHT app for iPad and NYTimes.com
   (worth $300 annually) so that you can get a balanced, intelligent perspective on global news, business, culture and sports at any time, wherever you happen to be in the world.
   Save up to 68% when you sign up for IHT home delivery today »

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

   Suzanne L. Strassburger is the president and C.E.O. of Strassburger Steaks in New York.

Steaks, the Family Business

By SUZANNE L. STRASSBURGER

   The C.E.O. of Strassburger Steaks says the meat business has been her family’s calling for five generations.

Career Couch

Defined by a Job, but Looking to Move On

By EILENE ZIMMERMAN

   If you want to move up in an organization, consultants suggest enlisting the help of others, including the boss, and to seek tasks that will showcase your skills for the new job.

Economic View

Give Me Your Tired, Your Poor and Your Economists, Too

By N. GREGORY MANKIW

   Many economists are receptive to the concept of immigration, partly because they tend to have a libertarian streak. But immigration has also benefited economists’ own profession.
   Migrant workers harvesting tomatoes in Florida.

Business and Labor Unite to Try to Alter Immigration Laws

By STEVEN GREENHOUSE

   Two oft-feuding groups, the A.F.L.-C.I.O. and the Chamber of Commerce, have formed an alliance to find a way for immigrants illegally in the United States to gain citizenship.
   A worker checks parts of a laptop on a Hewlett-Packard assembly line in Chongqing, China.

H.P. Directs Its Suppliers in China to Limit Student Labor

By KEITH BRADSHER and DAVID BARBOZA

   New rules from Hewlett-Packard, one of the world’s largest makers of computers and other tech products, reflect a major shift in how electronics companies view Chinese labor practices.

The Boss

Self-Reliance, Learned Early

By CAROL COLOMBO

   A chief executive learned as a girl that no job was beneath her — and that no job was above her, either.

Preoccupations

Maybe Management Isn’t Your Style

   Not everyone is cut out to be a supervisor, the author writes. When offered a management position, make sure that you really want it.

Post a Job

   Only by advertising through the New York Times can you reach 1 out of every 2 job seekers in New York. Your job will be automatically posted on Monster.com as well, and you have the option to
   place your ad in next Sunday's New York Times print edition, maximizing your target audience.
   Limited Time Offer
   Save $50

60 day Job Posting

   Save $50 on a 60 day day job posting!

   Now $345
   Act Now

Single Job Posting

   Find the right hire today and save with the following offers, each for $395.

   Post a job for 30 days online and get 4 lines of print in Sunday's paper *Ad must be completed by Thurs. at 5:59PM ET
   Post Now

   Post a job online-only for 60 days
   Post Now

Benefits

     * Post a job in minutes and start receiving qualified responses the same day.
     * Update your listing details as many times as you want.
     * Your ad can be read by 5.5 million readers in print and over 21.5 million readers online.

Target Post

   Take advantage of this new and affordable job posting product Target Post and instantly connect to local skilled, hourly, and administrative candidates. This offer is just $119.
   Post Now
     * Choose from 250 pre-defined job titles with matching descriptions.
     * Simplified one-step job posting process.
     * View and organize responses online.

Bulk Job Postings

   We’ve made purchasing and using bulk job postings as easy as can be. Simply buy as many postings you need and post jobs whenever you need to hire. Just log in to your account and click “Post a
   Job.” It’s that easy.
   Post Now
     * Plan ahead and
       save on every job posting.
     * Post any time you need to hire – bulk postings are good within 12 months.
     * You’ll receive responses instantly, making it easy to save, rank, and organize qualified resumes online.

                                                        24 hours a day, 7 days a week
   Display help wanted ad in the newspaper              212-556-8034
                                                        Mon-Fri, 9am - 5pm ET

   Finance, insurance, telecommunications, technology, book publishing, and utilities industries Mark A. Szollar, 212-556-3656, Szollma@nytimes.com
   Staffing firms (A-Z), pharmaceutical, transportation, healthcare, federal government, corporate, packaged goods, retail, hospitality, fashion industries, sports industries Tara Newton,

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

About

   Ralph Thomas Walker, who was hailed in The New York Times as the “architect of the century,” designed Walker Tower, which was completed in 1929.

   Walker Tower has now been transformed into 50 luxury condominium residences that incorporate the building’s original design details and includes all of the conveniences of modern, upscale
   residential living.

   The building’s elaborate brick façade has been painstakingly restored, as has the Art Deco ornamentation that Ralph Walker made famous through architectural masterpieces such as One Wall Street
   and the Barclay-Vesey Building.

   Read More »

News

   June 26th

   Today Walker Tower has its official sales launch, commemorated with an evening party for real estate industry leaders, media, and friends of the project, hosted by CORE. The event will take place
   in Walker Tower’s new fully furnished model residence.

   March 27th

   Rizzoli has announced a publication date of September 4, 2012, for Kathryn E. Holliday’s Ralph Walker: Architect of the Century, the first book dedicated to the career of the influential
   architect who designed what is now Walker Tower.

   offer available for readers who have not had home delivery within the past 90 days. Other restrictions apply.

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

Frequently Asked Questions

Digital Subscriptions

   What is a digital subscription? What do I get when I subscribe?

   A NYTimes digital subscription provides ongoing unlimited access to the NYTimes.com Web site from any computer or device, plus access to apps on portable devices. To get unlimited access to
   NYTimes.com and our NYTimes apps, you'll need a subscription. When you subscribe, you'll get unlimited access to articles and blog posts, as well as video, slide shows and other multimedia
   features — on the Web site, on the mobile site, and on our smartphone and tablet apps. With your digital subscription, you'll also get 100 Archive articles every four weeks. (NYTimes digital
   subscriptions do not include Premium Crosswords or The New York Times Crosswords apps.)

   Can I get a digital subscription to NYTimes.com only?

   No. The basic subscription package gives you unlimited access to NYTimes.com, plus the NYTimes apps for your smartphone.

   Are there digital subscription discounts for colleges and universities?

   Current college students, faculty and staff can save 50% on individual Times digital subscriptions. Restrictions apply. Visit our college rate page to learn more and begin the order process at
   this special rate. In addition, your college or university may purchase digital access at the college rate, under one bill, for a group of specific individuals. Group subscriptions are available
   for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, please contact edu@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   Do you have a group or corporate subscription program?

   Yes. We offer group subscriptions, which allow companies and organizations to purchase digital access for a set number of authorized users, under one bill, and at a special discount. Group
   subscriptions are available for all three digital subscription packages. To learn more, e-mail groupsubs@nytimes.com or call (800) 753-7795.

   What is the cancellation and refund policy?

   You can cancel your subscription at any time. When you cancel, we will stop charging your account the following billing cycle. Each billing cycle is four weeks, so your unlimited access will
   continue for the remainder of the current four-week period. Afterward, you will still be able to view 10 articles a month on NYTimes.com and read Top News on our apps at no charge, just like any
   other visitor.

   What if I don’t want to subscribe — can I still read NYTimes.com for free?

   Visitors get 10 free articles (including blog posts, slide shows, video and other multimedia features) each calendar month on NYTimes.com, as well as access to browse the home page, section
   fronts, blog fronts and classifieds. Subscribers enjoy unrestricted access to all of the content on NYTimes.com, and 100 Archive articles every four weeks. Also note that NYTimes apps are free to
   download and install, and they include the Top News section for free. Subscribers get unlimited access to all sections within the app.

   View our complete FAQ

Home Delivery Subscriptions

   With home delivery of The New York Times newspaper, do I get free digital access?

   Yes, only print subscribers get the added benefit of a free full digital access subscription which includes unlimited access to our New York Times Web site, NYTimes.com and the NYTimes apps for
   smartphones (iPhone®, Windows® Phone and Android™-powered phones) and tablets like the iPad®.

   Once I order home delivery, when can I start using my free digital benefits?

   To start using your free digital benefits, you'll need your New York Times home delivery account number. This will be sent to you in a confirmation e-mail once your order is placed. If you do not
   receive the e-mail you can call New York Times Customer Care at 1-800-NYTIMES (698-4637) and obtain the number.

   What time will The New York Times be delivered to my home?

   In most areas, the NYT will be delivered by 6:30 a.m. on weekdays, and 8:30 a.m. on Saturdays and Sundays.

   Can I suspend home delivery while I am on vacation?

   Yes, you can choose to receive credit for the period of your suspended delivery or donate your vacation credit to provide The New York Times newspaper to schools.

   View our complete FAQ

Living In | Van Cortlandt Village, the Bronx

   Houses on Van Cortlandt Park West, framed by apartment buildings, typify the real estate in this hilly perch just north of the Jerome Park Reservoir.

Affordability, and Pride of Place

By ALISON GREGOR

   Less expensive homes with many of the assets of Westchester County, minus the heavy tax burden.
     * Slide Show

     * More Living In Columns »

Living In | Millstone, N.J.

   Open space is well protected in Millstone. This house on Center Hill Drive has company, but not exactly within shouting distance.

Street Lighting by Mother Nature

By JILL P. CAPUZZO

   This Monmouth County township has an off-the-grid atmosphere and not much in the way of streetlights.
     * Slide Show

     * More Living In Columns »

Living In | Monroe, Conn.

   The outdoors is a big draw in Monroe, where skaters off Hattertown Road recently took advantage of cold, bright weather.

A Friend, in Need and Deed

By LISA PREVOST

   A family-oriented community that has shown its true colors in aiding Newtown, Conn., its neighbor to the north.
     * Slide Show

     * More Living In Columns »

Living In | Tudor City

   As seen from the park just opposite, the triptych of Tudor Tower — in an enclave perched above East 42nd Street — flaunts its facade adornments.

Merry Old Efficiency

By C. J. HUGHES

   The candy dish of details on each tower of Tudor City, on the far East Side of Manhattan, proves that a master-planned complex doesn’t have to be bland — and can even live up to its English name.
     * Slide Show

     * More Living In Columns »

Living In | Baychester, the Bronx

   MIDDLE GROUND Haffen Park offers a pool and a range of other recreation. Baychester, a home base for new arrivals from the Caribbean, has affordable real estate. It also happens to be a popular
   place to buy a car.

A Place for Renters to Buy In

By ALISON GREGOR

   A North Bronx neighborhood has gained a reputation for stability and affordability, drawing young couples and former renters.
     * More Living In Columns »

Living In | Richmond Hill

   POLYCHROME Shoppers on Liberty Avenue in Richmond Hill, whose residential populations include immigrants from South America and South Asia — and whose housing in spots is pure 19th-century
   American.

Indo-Caribbean Content, Victorian Style

By VERA HALLER

   In a neighborhood in southeastern Queens, you can eat Caribbean cuisine, shop for Bollywood movies, worship at a Sikh temple and stroll through streets lined with Victorian-era houses, a slice of
   pure Americana.
     * Slide Show

     * More Living In Columns »

Living In | Commack, L.I.

   HISTORIC ECHO Merging the surnames of two families of early European settlers, the Carll Burr House, a landmark in Commack, is still in private hands. The Burrs once bred and raised trotting
   horses; today the area is better known for its schools and its affordable real estate.

Sensible, Even on Scarlett Drive and Rhett Court

By AILEEN JACOBSON

   Shopping and affordable real estate are in abundant supply in Commack, a Suffolk County community not far from the North Shore beaches.
     * Slide Show

     * More Living In Columns »

Living In | Chelsea

   TASTE SPECTRUM The Antiques Garage, a weekend flea market on West 25th, reflects the eclecticism of Chelsea, whose converted factories and other old buildings house a mix of big-name shops,
   luxury condos and affordable housing.

Calling Activists and Artists of All Stripes

By C. J. HUGHES

   The area has evolved away from its factory origins with all kinds of residents — artists, middle-class Latinos and a gay community — living happily side by side.
     * Slide Show

     * More Living In Columns »

   A tranquil enclave of leafy streets and picturesque single-family homes in the area of the Jerome Park Reservoir.

   Because of strict zoning, many neighborhoods in this Monmouth County township consist of just a few large houses on sizable properties.

   A family-oriented community has ranches, split-levels and colonials, most built after 1940.

   An enclave with its own parks in the shadow of the United Nations is mainly co-ops, a lot of them rented out by their owners.

   A diverse part of Queens, made up of single- and multifamily homes with a smattering of apartment buildings.

   Tucked behind the highways and the shopping areas on busy streets are quiet neighborhoods, most created from the 1950s to the 1980s.

   A 27-block neighborhood with a diverse housing stock, from low-slung to high-rise, and affordable to luxury.

   A village in southern Westchester has a diverse housing stock that includes Tudors, colonials, contemporaries and apartments, in many price ranges.
     * Related Article

Living In | Springfield Gardens, Queens

   Springfield Gardens is a midsize middle-class enclave in southeastern Queens Queens 14 miles from Manhattan.
